{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509215"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11404"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11404"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.09,0.13,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4040"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84796"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4040"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69093"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"99"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2664"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42590"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman is reviewed on the cardiology ward with increasing shortness of breath over several days. She was admitted one week ago with an acute myocardial infarction and underwent percutaneous coronary intervention. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. Her medications include aspirin, ticagrelor, metoprolol, and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly distressed. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a new pansystolic murmur at the apex that radiates to the axilla and increases in intensity with expiration and sustained handgrip.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following murmurs would be enhanced by this manoeuvre and best fits the clinical scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mitral regurgitation","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","Aortic stenosis","Tricuspid regurgitation","Pulmonary stenosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of acute mitral regurgitation following myocardial infarction. The handgrip manoeuvre increases systemic vascular resistance and afterload, which has different effects on various cardiac murmurs. \u003Cstrong\u003EMitral regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E murmurs increase in intensity with handgrip due to increased left ventricular pressure causing more regurgitant flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertrophic cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E murmurs decrease with handgrip because the increased afterload reduces the left ventricular outflow gradient. This dynamic obstruction typically produces a harsh systolic ejection murmur that also decreases with squatting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E murmurs decrease with handgrip due to reduced flow across the stenotic valve when afterload increases. This helps differentiate it from mitral regurgitation, as both can present as systolic murmurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETricuspid regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E murmurs are right-sided and therefore increase with inspiration rather than expiration. The handgrip manoeuvre primarily affects left-sided murmurs through its effect on systemic vascular resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is also a right-sided murmur that increases with inspiration. Like tricuspid regurgitation, it is not significantly affected by the handgrip manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical context is particularly important here - acute mitral regurgitation is a known complication of myocardial infarction, occurring due to papillary muscle dysfunction or rupture. This can lead to rapid onset heart failure, as seen in this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The handgrip manoeuvre increases systemic vascular resistance, enhancing mitral regurgitation murmurs and diminishing aortic stenosis murmurs","Acute mitral regurgitation is a serious complication of myocardial infarction due to papillary muscle dysfunction or rupture","Left-sided murmurs typically increase with expiration, while right-sided murmurs increase with inspiration"],"references":["Salazar S, Borrero J, Harris D. On systolic murmurs and cardiovascular physiological maneuvers. Advances in Physiology Education [Internet]. 2012 [cited 27 July 2022];36(4):251-256. Available from: https://journals.physiology.org/doi/full/10.1152/advan.00128.2011?rfr_dat=cr_pub++0pubmed\u0026url_ver=Z39.88-2003\u0026rfr_id=ori%3Arid%3Acrossref.org"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69093"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11404"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69093"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-11T12:58:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-11T12:58:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"i